ported.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I have written </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">previously </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">about the MoJ’s </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">original </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">proposals, and in particular (a) the residence test and (b) permission fees, and my analysis is co</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ntained in the special edition of the journal </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> (2013, issue 3), which has I think </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">(and hope) </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">been made available to members of the Committee. It gathers together a considerable volume of relevant material. I will happily ensure that members have further copies. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">To arrange further copies, please j</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ust email me on </span><a href="mailto:michaelfordham@blackstonechambers.com"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">michaelfordham@blackstonechambers.com</span></a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">In my responses, including </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">this document, I give my own </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">personal and professional view.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I will focus on public law, including judicial review and human rights, because t</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">hose are my areas o</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">f expertise. That is not intended, for a moment, to detract from other matters. It is simply to focus my attention to issues on which I think I can speak from a position of knowledge and experience, as an insider.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I have been practising in </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">judicial review </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">and human rights</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> for 23 years. I am author of a leading textbook, in its sixth edition; and co-editor of a quarterly practitioner journal. I was for many years a member of the Attorney General’s A Panel of Counsel, and I have represented the Government at </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">all levels of the Courts and in Strasbourg. I have won awards including Human Rights Lawyer of the Year, Public Law Junior of the Year, Human Rights QC of the Year, and the Bar Pro Bono Award. I am a Visiting Fellow of the Bingham Centre for the Rule of La</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">w, College Lecturer in administrative law at Hertford College Oxford, a Bencher of Gray’s Inn, a civil and criminal Recorder, a Deputy Judge of the Upper Tribunal and a Deputy High Court Judge sitting in the Administrative Court.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">should make this clear:</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> I </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">am convinced that </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">there are </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">many </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ways</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> in which public law litigation, including judicial review, could be reformed to protect and save public money. I am personally and professionally committed to exploring what steps can be taken, consistently with the</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> rule of law and access to justice. I intend to try to put myself at the forefront of work in this area.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I am </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">also convinced that there must be core irreducible minimum standards for access to justice and the rule of law, including effective lega</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">l representation funded by the State. There must be a threshold which austerity and budgetary considerations must not be permitted to </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">penetrate and undermine. Legal aid, like prisons and judges, is a necessary part of a functioning legal system. They can </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">enjoy no immunity from cuts. But there must be a bedrock baseline at which they need to be defended and protected, at which point cost-saving can no longer be seen as a legitimate justification.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I believe that the MoJ’s proposals strike at those core stand</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ards. I also believe that, if proceeded with, there will be legal challenges. I expect them to succeed. But it ought not to come to that. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">And much damage will have been done. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">The voice of wisdom </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">must</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> speak now.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">It is no interest of mine to defend lawyers </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">and their livelihoods. I believe it is right for lawyers to be judged, and in the public arena, by the value of what they do. My interest is in effective legal advice and representation which people need, in order to secure access to justice and the vindic</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ation of the rule of law. That is not meant to sound pompous. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I have had the privilege to observe first-hand skilled legal aid practitioners at the coal-face, working relentless long hours in challenging cases, from one urgent high-pressure piece of work t</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">o the next. It is a practical </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">reality. Those lawyers can and should be</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> judged by the value of what they do. Their work is vocational, not wealth-driven. It is the equivalent of the </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">National Health Service</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, for the law. What those lawyers do on public fundi</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ng is, as I have said elsewhere, the beating heart of the rule of law.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">These proposals threaten to drive th</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ose committed and skilled professionals</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> out of practice, leaving individuals without effective advice and representation, many trying to represent th</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">emselves.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">There is another point. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Public law litigation involves the legal rights of the individual, as against the State. This is not about funding private individuals to sue one another. That means the consequences and implications are that – in making </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">publicly funded representation unavailable –</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Government is</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> insulating </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">itself f</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">rom effective legal challenge</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. Government can avoid inconvenient truths, and rid itself of turbulent priests.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Permission-stage fees</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">The Government’s basic idea is that those who</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> bring hopeless judicial review claims should not be expected to recover their fees from the public purse.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I agree with that basic idea.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Importantly</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">there is a good solution</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">can be put into practical effect. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Government has recently introduced a mec</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">hanism for a permission judge to certify claims as hopeless: </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">totally without merit</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. The obvious solution is for claimants’ lawyers not to recover their fees for issuing a claim which a Judge has certified as </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">totally without merit</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. The MoJ steadfastly ignor</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">es that solution. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">They will not even try it</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">The MoJ proposal will cut off the oxygen supply for claims which are properly </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">pursued. Government knows this. It is self-insulation from proper legal challenges, by the means of a suffoc</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ating deterrent.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> The rea</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">sons are as follows.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">First</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, the refusal of permission for judicial review does not mean that the claim was hopeless and should not have been brought by a competent and conscientious legal representative. What we are required to do is to make an informed, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">good faith assessment of the prospects of success. If a clinician assessed in good faith that operations have a better than 50% prospect of success, we would not ask the clinician to go without pay for every operation which does not in the event succeed. I</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">f the Government’s legal representatives assess in good faith that permission for judicial review should be resisted, we would not expect those lawyers to go without pay for every time permission is granted. Judges may take a different view about a case. T</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">hey frequently disagree with each other: that is why there is a right to renew the application for permission where it has been refused on the papers. Many judges apply very exacting standards of whether a case is viable. Moreover, by the time the case get</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">s to the judge the picture will often be different than it was when the claimant’s lawyer was doing their best on the information then available.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Secondly</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">the MoJ is not even speaking of withholding payment where permission is refused. It is speaking of withholding payment </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">unless permission is granted</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. There are many reasons why the responsible, cost-saving course will be for a claim to be withdrawn. For exa</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">mple: circumstances change, the decision being challenged is superseded by a favourable decision, or a lawful one. If the permission stage is not needed that does not mean that the claimant’s lawyers have acted irresponsibly. Generally, it will mean precis</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ely the opposite. It is no reassurance for practitioners to be told that they can make a special claim for a special discretion to be exercised in their favour. Even if that could address the problem, it would only be by introducing a new and costly form o</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">f satellite application, arguing about whether a claim was properly commenced.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Thirdly</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, this measure will have a disastrous chilling effect. It will, as I have said, have a self-insulating consequence. What is my conscientious instructing solicitor to do </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">when I advise that their judicial review case has – in my judgment – a 60/40 prospect of success? In order for the work to be viable, they need to know that </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">permission will be granted</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. It is very rare that I can say that. I can say permission should in my </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">judgment be granted; that I expect it to be granted. But I cannot say there will not be some point raised against us which persuades the Court. I cannot rule out a judge taking a negative view of the case, at the permission stage. It is like asking the cli</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">nician to say that the operation </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">will be a success</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. Or asking the defendant’s representative to say permission </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">will be refused</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. Nor can I say that we will be proceeding to permission. I cannot say there will be no development; no fresh decision; no change </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">of circumstances. I certainly cannot say a residual discretion will be favourably exercised, if there is some development. Solicitors cannot operate a legal aid practice, at rates which are cut to the bone, where they are doing substantial work for which t</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">hey may not be paid.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Let me describe a scenario. It is a real one. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">There may be 10 viable cases, assessed conscientiously and in good faith. For various reasons, it may be that only 8 need permission, and only 6 receive permission. The 2 that are refused permission are not certified as totally without merit. The truth is </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">that the lawyers will not be able to take any of these 10 cases. That is because we cannot predict which 2 will not need permission, and which 2 will be refused permission; and a legal aid firm cannot function if it is only paid for 60% of its work. This s</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">cenario means Government is insulated from </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">all 10 cases</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, including 6 cases which the permission judge would grant permission. It means the claimants in all these cases cannot secure effective representation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">The proposal is a bad one. The solution is the </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">one I have outlined </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">at §1</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> above.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Prisoners and foreigners</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I will address these two </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">proposals</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> together. The MoJ proposes to have general exclusions, with some exceptions, cutting legal aid for judicial review claims brought by (a) prisoners and (b) non-residents.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">I would like to outline why I regard these as troubling</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">reprehensible proposals.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">F</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">irst</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">it is important to identify the premise. These exclusions are not about permission-stage costs where permission is refused: the MoJ has addressed permission costs separately, as have I. The logic here for judicial review extends to – and is all about</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> – judicial review cases </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">which are appropriate for permission</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. What is designed to be excluded are cases properly brought. That is important, because the permission stage operates to filter out: (a) cases which lack a realistic prospect of success; (b) cas</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">es where there is suitable alternative remedy; (c) cases which are lacking in practical substance (because they are premature, hypothetical, or the alleged unlawfulness is not material to the practical outcome). So – the premise is that there is a proper j</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">udicial review case brought on behalf of a prisoner or a non-resident, which (a) has a realistic prospect of success; (b) has no suitable alternative remedy; and (c) is a matter of practical substance.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Secondly</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, it is quite wrong </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">in principle </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">to say fundi</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ng </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">for prisoner judicial review </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">is unnecessary because there are suitable alternative remedies. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">In fact, judicial review applies only where there is none. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">The Courts address that very question, and will only grant permission for judicial review where there</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> is no suitable alternative remedy. If there is </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">a suitable alternative remedy</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, defendants can point to it and permission is refused. In the field of prisoners’ rights, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">the Home Office</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">argued in the 1980s</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> that judicial should be excluded because there were </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">alternative remedies</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. The Courts dealt with those arguments, and </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">the House of Lords decided that</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> judicial review was necessary, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">and no exclusion could be justified: the case is </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Leech</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> [1988] AC 533. Now the MoJ is seeking to do what the Home Office failed t</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">o do: justify an exclusion. Many of the leading human rights cases in the United Kingdom have been prisoner judicial review cases: cases like </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Simms</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Anderson</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Daly</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. A good practical example is </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Russell</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> [2000] 1 WLR 2027, where prisoners were being den</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ied adequate food.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Thirdly</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">the need for non-residents to access practical and effective remedies on judicial review cannot seriously be doubted. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">From Lord Scarman in </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Khawaja</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> to Lord Bingham in </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Belmarsh</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, the Courts have recognised the importance of equality under the law, when non-residents are owed public law obligations by British public authorities. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">In the Iraq cases, the Government argued that the Human Rights Act was not intended to give practical a</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">nd effective remedies to those beyond our shores: </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">examples like </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Baha Mousa when he was beaten to death by British soldiers; Al-Jedda when he was interned without recourse to law. The House of Lords decided that Parliament </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">did</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> intend practical and effective</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> remedies to be available under the Human Rights Act. Every time the </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">spotlight is shone, through judicial review cases in the English Courts, on human rights abuses overseas, the Government talks the talk. It speaks of how important</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> it is to get to the tru</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">th, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">learn the lessons. It sets up public inquiries, arising out of judicial review. It tells the Courts how important it is that </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">protective standards are complied with: for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">policies on Afghanistan detention and handovers</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">to foreign interrogators</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">All of this provides comfort</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. There</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> could not be unlawful and unaccountable extraordinary rendition by British forces; there could not be a British Guantanamo Bay. </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Please m</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ake no mistake: the Iraq judicial review cases were possible </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">only</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> because there was </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">legal aid. Personally, I have known no prouder moment in my career than speaking up for civilians subjected to human rights abuses overseas, because a British Court can give a practical and effective remedy in cases with effective legal representat</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ion on B</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ritish legal aid. It is </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">no accident that those Iraq cases, fought over many years, produced no fewer than five winners of </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">the annual </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Liberty/JUSTICE Human Rights Lawyer of the Year</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> award</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> The MoJ’s position</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, through this proposal, must be that such cases</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">hould not be publicly funded, which would mean they could never be brought. The story of Baha Mousa would never be told.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> This is the road to human rights impunity.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Fourthly</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, the concerns are not answered by saying funding can be granted in special cases. For the exclusions to be meaningful, in saving public funds, it must be the case that viable claims which could previously be brought with effective representation, to estab</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">lish unlawfulness by a public authority, are not now to be brought with effective representation. If it is the case that all viable prisoner judicial review cases can be brought – with civil legal aid rather than criminal legal aid – then there can be no c</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ost-saving, but different labels are used and claimants are denied expertise from those with criminal legal aid arrangements. The MoJ’s idea is </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">that non-residents could</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> obtain funding where the refusal of funding is a violation of EU law or human rights. T</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">hat risks introducing another set of costly satellite applications. Its logic is clear. If you are a non-resident, then it is not enough that you can show that a public authority has breached your rights. You have to show a second breach: that the legal ai</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">d authorities are also breaching your rights </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in not providing you public funding</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">. That is designed and intended to keep out of the Courts </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">(or at least away from effective representation) </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">cases where public authorities have acted unlawfully; where the claim</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">ant lacks means</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> to afford a lawyer</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">but where the claimant </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">strong </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">legal merits, and has no alternative remedy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">Thank you for </span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt">addressing these most anxious matters.</span><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:12pt"> Please speak out.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>